# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: andrea-fischer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in Germany on 27 September 1998 to elect the members of the 14th Bundestag.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] The Social Democratic Party (SPD) emerged as the largest faction in parliament for the first time since 1972, with its leader Gerhard Schröder becoming chancellor.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] The Christian Democrats had their worst election result since 1949.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] Since German reunification on 3 October 1990, the unemployment rate in Germany had risen from 4.2% to 9.4% in 1998, with the Federal Labor Office registering more than 4 million unemployed.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] The unified Germany had to fight economic and domestic difficulties even as it actively participated in the project of European integration.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] Most people blamed the centre-right coalition government of the Christian Democratic Union/Christian Social Union (CDU/CSU) and the Free Democratic Party (FDP) for the economic difficulties.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] Longtime Chancellor Helmut Kohl's government was regarded by many as not having fully implemented the unification after eight years, in view of the mass protests in many eastern German towns due to job losses and social welfare cuts.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] The 1998 campaign began with both the CDU and SPD working out who would lead their parties.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] There had been rumours that Kohl would resign and allow Wolfgang Schäuble to take the reins of the CDU, but these rumours were rendered obsolete when Kohl announced in April 1997 that he would seek the chancellorship for a sixth term.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] The two contenders for the SPD nomination were Oskar Lafontaine, the party's chairman, and Gerhard Schröder, Minister-President of Lower Saxony.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] On 1 March 1998, Schröder led the SPD to a huge victory in the Lower Saxony state election, gaining an unusual absolute majority for the second time and effectively receiving the SPD nomination for federal chancellor.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] Schröder had announced he would withdraw his bid for the nomination if he received below 42 percent of the popular vote.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] In the 1998 general elections, Schröder received 47.9 percent.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] Following this election, Lafontaine withdrew his bid and Schröder was inaugurated in the May 1998 convention.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] For the SPD, Schröder offered a new face for the party.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] He gave the party a new vigor, one that was lacking in the CDU after Kohl proclaimed his nomination.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] Many in the CDU questioned if Kohl had made the right choice for the party.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] The CDU campaign was based on the experience and reputation of Kohl.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] One of the CDU's main slogans was 'Safety, not Risks.' "Kohl exploited his familiarity and experience, as well as his status as Europe's longest serving head of government." The SPD on the other hand ran the campaign using strategies developed in the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] The SPD set up election headquarters and introduced 'rapid rebuttal units' not unlike those used by Bill Clinton of the United States in his successful presidential bid in 1992.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] The SPD avoided direct attacks at Kohl, but rather focused on their message of a "new center".
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] The FDP had usually ridden on the coattails of the CDU, and was mostly disapproved in the polls.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] With the SPD well ahead in the polls, many of the voters from the CDU had fewer incentives to vote for the FDP.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] The FDP was also having trouble projecting a coherent platform to voters.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] The Greens too were having issues concerning their platform.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] The two factions in the Greens, the fundamentalists and the pragmatists, had problems settling on their platform since the founding of the Green party.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] The major issue of the 1998 campaign was unemployment.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] In 1996, the unemployment rate in Germany surpassed the government's "limit" of 4 million unemployed people.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] Both parties blamed high labor costs, high taxes and the high welfare costs as the causes of the problem.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] During the campaign, Schröder used this issue against Kohl, calling him 'the unemployment chancellor.' Unemployment was worst in the former East Germany.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] While the national rate stood at 9.4 percent, former East Germany was suffering with unemployment at 20 percent.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] Many in the former East Germany blamed Kohl for the slow economic recovery.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] Another issue at hand were Germany's tax and welfare reforms.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] While the CDU/CSU had offered proposals to reduce benefits in healthcare and pensions, the SPD controlled Bundesrat secured the passage of the bill.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] The proposed bill also offered tax cuts that were to benefit the rich, something the SPD opposed.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] While Kohl continually pushed the issue of European integration, the issue fell short from voters' minds.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] Schröder, on the other hand, almost ignored the issue.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] Many voters in Germany had other concerns besides the European Union.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] Toward the end of the campaign, polls placed the CDU/CSU and FDP coalition in a tie with the SPD and Green coalition.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] Despite these polls, the final numbers told a different story.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] The SPD-Green coalition won an unexpectedly large victory, taking 345 seats and earning a strong majority in the Bundestag—the first centre-left absolute majority in post-World War II Germany.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] The SPD won 40.9 percent of the vote, due to an increase of 4.5 percent from 1994.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU-FDP coalition had gone into the election with a solid majority and 341 seats, but was cut down to 288 seats.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU lost 6.2% of its 1994 vote, and lost 109 electoral districts to the SPD.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] Germany's mixed-member proportional system, in which a slate of statewide delegates are elected alongside the electorate delegates, softened the blow somewhat, so the CDU/CSU only suffered a net loss of 49 seats.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] It was still the CDU/CSU's worst defeat ever.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] By contrast, their junior coalition partner, the FDP, netted a loss of just 4 seats.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] The SPD swept all single-member constituency seats in the states of Brandenburg, Saxony-Anhalt, Saarland, Bremen, Hamburg and (for the first and last time) Schleswig-Holstein.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] Kohl lost his own constituency of Ludwigshafen, though he was still re-elected to the Bundestag through the Rhineland-Palatinate CDU party list, and he had not won the seat in the 1983 and 1987 elections.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] Future Chancellor Angela Merkel only narrowly won her constituency of Stralsund – Rügen – Grimmen with only 37.3 percent of the vote; the only time she got less than 40 percent of the vote.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] A new government was formed by a coalition between the SPD and the Greens, with the SPD's Gerhard Schröder as chancellor and Greens leader Joschka Fischer as vice-chancellor and foreign minister.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] It was the first red-green coalition government at the federal level in Germany, as well as the first purely centre-left government in post-World War II Germany.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] Kohl stepped down as chairman of the CDU, as did CSU chairman Theodor Waigel.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] The 1998 German election was historic in many ways.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] It resulted in a centre-right government being succeeded by a left-wing one—the first in postwar Germany (the SPD's previous term in government had been at the helm of a centre-left coalition).
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] In addition, it brought to an end the sixteen-year rule of Kohl – the second-longest of any German chancellor, and the longest tenure for a democratically elected head of government in German history.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] It has been compared to the defeat of Winston Churchill in 1945 – both were seen as conservative wartime leaders, and in both cases both were turned out of office by the electorate once the war was over.
[src:andrea-fischer/1998-german-federal-election] Churchill was ousted before World War II was even over, while Kohl managed to hang onto power for two more terms after the reunification of Germany (which is often considered to be the end of the Cold War).
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] The **2011 Berlin state election** was held on 18 September 2011 to elect the members of the 17th Abgeordnetenhaus of Berlin.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] The incumbent government consisting of the Social Democratic Party (SPD) and The Left lost its majority.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] The SPD lost five seats, remaining the largest party, while The Left lost three.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] The Christian Democratic Union (CDU) made small gains, while The Greens moved into third place with 30 seats.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] The Free Democratic Party (FDP) lost three-quarters of its votes and all its seats.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] The Pirate Party contested its first Berlin state election and won fifteen seats with 8.9% of the vote.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] This was the first time the party had been elected to a state parliament anywhere in Germany.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] The SPD initially sought a coalition with The Greens, but talks broke down over the extension of the Bundesautobahn 100.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] A coalition agreement between the SPD and CDU was finalised in November, with Mayor Klaus Wowereit continuing in office.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] The table below lists parties represented in the 16th Abgeordnetenhaus of Berlin.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] The CDU considered safety on the Berlin U-Bahn an issue after a number of attacks on the property of the U-Bahn.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] The party published material using images from attacks captioned with the question "Safe?" These were later recalled.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] The CDU also posted billboards comparing the number of police officers cut from the force by the red-red coalition with the number of crimes committed on the city's buses and U-Bahn trains.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] Nils Diederich, a professor of political science at the Free University of Berlin, stated prior to the election that he did not believe this would be much of an issue due to a positive mood within the city.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] The Free Democratic Party (FDP) representation was removed from the Abgeordnetenhaus of Berlin after they failed to reach the 5% threshold.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] This was the fifth time in 2011 in Germany that the Free Democrats failed to obtain representation in a state parliament.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] They also lost representation in Saxony-Anhalt, Rhineland-Palatinate, Bremen and Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] Baden-Württemberg and Hamburg are the only states in which they reached the 5% electoral threshold in that year.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] The win in Berlin marks the 7th time out of seven elections in 2011 that the Social Democrats got into government.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] On 21 September 2011, election officials found that the results of the Green Party and The Left were inadvertently swapped in the Lichtenberg district.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] Evrim Baba-Sommer of the Green Party will replace Karin Seidel-Kalmutzki of the Social Democratic Party.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] On 22 September 2011, Norbert Kopp, the district mayor for Steglitz-Zehlendorf, confirmed at least 379 postal ballots had found their way into the bin of a block of flats.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] The ballots were properly sent to the Zehlendorf city hall and the votes could change a number of the local council seats.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] The police have started an investigation over the incident.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] Initially, the Social Democrats concentrated on forming a coalition with the Greens.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] However, on 5 October 2011, coalition talks between the SPD and the Greens broke down.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] The disagreement was about the extension of Bundesautobahn 100.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] The Green Party platform had insisted on not extending the Bundesautobahn 100.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] The Social Democrats offered a compromise to not go ahead with the 3.2 km extension A100 if the €420 million provided by the federal government could be invested in other transportation infrastructure projects.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] However, the federal government rejected the possibility of transferring the money to other projects.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] Müller pointed out to the Greens "that the Red-Green coalition would only have a one-vote majority compared to the stable 10-vote majority which would be achieved in coalition with the CDU".
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] Wolfgang Thierse, deputy Parliamentary group leader, stated "that he was surprised and a little disappointed at the breakdown of talks" and "Just as Red-Green would not have been heaven for Berlin, Red-Black would not be hell".
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] Renate Künast, leader of the Berlin Chapter of the Green Party, stated that Klaus Wowereit "wanted a surrender, and no coalition".
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] The Social Democrats therefore continued talks with the Christian Democrats so that a grand coalition that would govern Berlin was finalized on 16 November 2011.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] According to the 100-page coalition agreement, Wowereit will continue as mayor.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] Disagreements between the two parties have been settled.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] There will be for example a "City tax" of 5% for hotel guests beginning in 2013 and the minimum wage for public contract jobs will increase by €1 per hour (currently at €7.50).
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] Plans were dropped for making teachers civil servants again and requiring property owners to contribute to street improvement costs.
[src:andrea-fischer/2011-berlin-state-election] Wowereit summarised the talks by saying "We want Berlin to become richer and to stay sexy".
[src:andrea-fischer/achim-großmann] After graduating from high school in 1966 at the Kaiser-Karls-Gymnasium in Aachen, Großmann studied psychology at the TH Aachen, which he completed in 1972 with a diploma in psychology.
[src:andrea-fischer/achim-großmann] He then worked as an educational consultant at the advice center for parents, children and young people in Alsdorf until 1986, and as its director since 1979.
[src:andrea-fischer/achim-großmann] At the same time, he worked for several semesters as a lecturer in administrative psychology at the University of Applied Sciences for Public Administration in Aachen.
[src:andrea-fischer/achim-großmann] Achim Großmann was divorced and had two children.
[src:andrea-fischer/achim-großmann] From 1975 to 1998, Großmann was a councilor for the city of Würselen.
[src:andrea-fischer/achim-großmann] After the 1998 federal election, he was appointed Parliamentary State Secretary to the Federal Minister for Transport, Construction and Housing in the Government led by Gerhard Schröder.
[src:andrea-fischer/achim-großmann] After the formation of the Grand Coalition under Chancellor Angela Merkel, the ministry was renamed the Federal Ministry of Transport, Building and Urban Development.
[src:andrea-fischer/achim-großmann] After the 2009 federal election and the subsequent change in government, Großmann left office in October 2009.
[src:andrea-fischer/achim-großmann] In his eleven years in office, he served under five different construction and transport ministers.
[src:andrea-fischer/achim-großmann] As Parliamentary State Secretary, Achim Großmann was a member of the supervisory board of Deutsche Bahn and was involved in the preparations for the IPO.
[src:andrea-fischer/adelheid-d-tröscher] She attended grammar school and high school in Ithaca, New York, United States, graduating in 1959.
[src:andrea-fischer/adelheid-d-tröscher] She then studied education, history and English language and literature in Marburg, Jugenheim an der Bergstraße and Frankfurt am Main and passed her first and second state examinations to become a teacher at secondary schools.
[src:andrea-fischer/adelheid-d-tröscher] In 1962 she was accepted into the teaching profession and from 1975 to 1976 she worked in the school department of the Regierungspräsidium Darmstadt.
[src:andrea-fischer/adelheid-d-tröscher] From 1986 to 1992, she was head of the Paul Hindemith Comprehensive School in Frankfurt am Main.
[src:andrea-fischer/adelheid-d-tröscher] After leaving the parliamentary group in the Bundestag of her own accord, she became involved in the SPD on a voluntary basis, particularly in the *Forum One World*, which deals with development policy issues.
[src:andrea-fischer/adelheid-d-tröscher] She also heads the Rhine-Main regional group of Transparency International.
[src:andrea-fischer/adelheid-d-tröscher] She is also involved as chairwoman of the Citoyen Foundation, which supports civic engagement and is particularly concerned with the artistic and aesthetic education of children and young people.
[src:andrea-fischer/adelheid-d-tröscher] Tröscher is the daughter of Tassilo Tröscher.
[src:andrea-fischer/adelheid-d-tröscher] From 1972 to 1977, from 1981 to 1989 and in 1991 she was a city councillor of the city of Frankfurt am Main, and from 1992 to 1993 a full-time district councillor of the Kreis Offenbach.
[src:andrea-fischer/adelheid-d-tröscher] From November 1994 to October 2002, Tröscher was a member of the German Bundestag for two terms.
[src:andrea-fischer/adelheid-d-tröscher] In the 1994 Bundestag election, she entered parliament via the SPD state list, and in the 1998 Bundestag election she won the direct mandate in the constituency 144 (Odenwald).
[src:andrea-fischer/adelheid-d-tröscher] From 1994 to 2002, she was a member of the Committee on Economic Cooperation and Development and from 1996 to 2002, she was the SPD parliamentary group's spokesperson on development policy.
[src:andrea-fischer/adelheid-d-tröscher] Tröscher is a member of GEW, AWO, Kinderschutzbund, Pro Familia and medico international.
[src:andrea-fischer/adelheid-d-tröscher] In 1999 she became a member of the board of trustees and the administrative committee of Deutsche Stiftung für internationale Entwicklung (DSE) and a member of German Foundation for International Development.
[src:andrea-fischer/adelheid-d-tröscher] (DSE) and a member of German Agro Action.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-dess] Albert Dess graduated from Agricultural college in 1966.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-dess] He obtained his Master's in agriculture in 1979.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-dess] Albert had a Secondary occupation as farmer and worked in commerce and industry.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-dess] He became managing director of a farming cooperative and in 1977, a Full-time farmer/training establishment.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-dess] In 1974 Albert Dess became the District Chairman of the Junge Union.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-dess] In 1981 he became a Member of the CSU district executive and later in 1984, he became the Municipal Chairman of the CSU.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-dess] He later rose in ranks by becoming the District Chairman in 1987, Regional Vice-chairman (1989–1995) and Regional Chairman (1995) of the CSU Agricultural Association.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-dess] Albert was a Member of the CSU district executive from 1989 and in 1997, a member of the CSU Regional Executive Committee.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-dess] From 1972 to 1996 he was in the Municipal Councillor, Berngau.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-dess] He became a District Councillor, Neumarkt/Oberpfalz in 1978.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-dess] In 1984–1996, he was the Vice-chairman of Neumarkt/Oberpfalz district council and from 1984 to 1996, the Mayor of Berngau.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-dess] Albert Dess from 1992 to 2004 was the Farm policy spokesman for the CSU Regional Group in the Bundestag and from 1997 to 2004, a Member of the CDU/CSU Group Executive Committee.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-dess] He later became the Chairman of the CSU Regional Group working party for Agriculture, Consumer Protection, Environment, Transport, Building and Energy from 2000 to 2004.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-dess] Dess was a member of the European Parliament's Committee on Agriculture and Rural Development (AGRI).
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-dess] He was a substitute for the Committee on International Trade (INTRA), a member of the delegation for relations with Mercosur and a substitute for the delegation to the ACP-EU Joint Parliamentary Assembly.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-dess] In May 2018, Dess announced that he would not stand in the 2019 European elections but instead resign from active politics by the end of the parliamentary term.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-dess] Outside Germany, Dess is best known for trying to introduce in the European Parliament a Volkswagen-written piece of legislation that would have exempted a whole class of vehicle from pollution controls.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-dess] The proposal was dropped after the Volkswagen emissions violation scandal erupted and Dress has thus far refused requests to comment on his actions.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-probst] Probst was born in Garching bei München, Upper Bavaria.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-probst] After graduation in 1951 from the Maximilians Gymnasium in Munich, Probst took an agricultural apprenticeship.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-probst] He then studied agricultural sciences at the Technical University of Munich, graduating in 1958 with a diploma as an agricultural engineer.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-probst] In Munich, he served in the Catholic student group K.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-probst] He then joined the agricultural civil service, working at the milk research institute at TU Munich.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-probst] He left this institute in 1961, after completing research.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-probst] He returned to TU Munich in 1963, after two years as an agriculture adviser in France, to work on a research project concerning population genetics.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-probst] At this time he began to participate in municipal politics.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-probst] Probst was deputy chair of the culture team of the Christian Socialist Union for many years.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-probst] From 1960 to 1973 he belonged to the country of the circle day of the district of Munich.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-probst] He was also a member of the Garching local council from 1966 until 1990.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-probst] From 1969 to 1998 Probst was a member of the German Bundestag.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-probst] He was chair of the Committee on Development and Science from 1972 to 1976, and from 1976 to 1982 chaired the Committee on Research and Technology.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-probst] Until 1982, he chaired the science development team and served as spokesperson for the Christian Socialist Union rural group.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-probst] Probst was a directly selected delegate of the Munich/Freising constituency in the Bundestag.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-probst] From 1991 to 1999 he represented Germany at parliamentary meetings of the Council of Europe, and at the European Union.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-probst] On 4 October 1982 Probst became Parliamentary Secretary of State at the Federal Ministry for Research and Technology, in the federal government led by Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-probst] Here he advocated the early provision of computers in schools.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-probst] He served until the Bundestag election in 1990, leaving government on 24 January 1991.
[src:andrea-fischer/albert-probst] Probst is married and has four children.
[src:andrea-fischer/alexander-bonde] In 1992 and 1993 Bonde was an exchange student at Kahuku High School (Oahu, Hawaii, USA).
[src:andrea-fischer/alexander-bonde] From 2002 to 2011, Bonde was a member of the Bundestag.
[src:andrea-fischer/alexander-bonde] There he represented his constituency *283 Emmendingen-Lahr*, a rural area in the Black Forest that covers 41 municipalities in the state of Baden-Württemberg.
[src:andrea-fischer/alexander-bonde] Bonde was first elected in 2002 and was reelected in 2005 and 2009.
[src:andrea-fischer/alexander-bonde] Bonde served on the Defense Committee and on the Budget Committee.
[src:andrea-fischer/alexander-bonde] He was also a member of the Financial Markets Committee that supervises the German banking rescue package.
[src:andrea-fischer/alexander-bonde] On the Budget Committee, Bonde served as “rapporteur-general” for agriculture (the equivalent to chairing a small subcommittee) as “rapporteur” (equivalent to being a member of a small subcommittee) for defence, economy and labor.
[src:andrea-fischer/alexander-bonde] From 2008 to 2010, Bonde was a member of the parliamentary body providing oversight of the Special Financial Market Stabilization Funds (SoFFin).
[src:andrea-fischer/alexander-bonde] In addition to his committee assignments, Bonde served as vice-chairman of the German-American Parliamentary Group and of the Aviation & Space Caucus of the German Bundestag.
[src:andrea-fischer/alexander-bonde] In 2011, Bonde was appointed State Minister for Rural Areas, Agriculture and Consumer Rights in the state government of Baden-Württemberg under Minister-President Winfried Kretschmann.
[src:andrea-fischer/alexander-bonde] In the negotiations to form a coalition government with the Christian Democratic Union (CDU) under the leadership of Kretschmann following the 2016 state elections, Bonde led his party’s delegation in the working group on rural affairs and consumer protection.
[src:andrea-fischer/alexander-bonde] On 12 May 2016 Peter Hauk (CDU) became his successor.
[src:andrea-fischer/alexander-bonde] In December 2017, the board of trustees of the German Federal Environment Foundation (DBU) – at the time chaired by Rita Schwarzelühr-Sutter – appointed Bonde as the organization's secretary general.
[src:andrea-fischer/alexander-bonde] In the negotiations to form another coalition government under Kretschmann's leadership following the 2021 state elections, Bonde was a member of the working group on climate, environmental policy and energy, co-chaired by Sandra Detzer and Andreas Jung.
[src:andrea-fischer/andrea-fischer] After graduating from high school, Andrea Fischer completed an apprenticeship as an offset printer.
[src:andrea-fischer/andrea-fischer] She then worked as a printer and proofreader and additionally completed her studies in economics at the Free University of Berlin.
[src:andrea-fischer/andrea-fischer] After completing her studies, she worked as a research assistant at the European Parliament, the WZB Berlin Social Science Center and the *Federal Insurance Institution for Employees* (*Bundesversicherungsanstalt für Angestellte*).
[src:andrea-fischer/andrea-fischer] She has been a member of the German Green Party since 1985, before that she was a member of the Group of International Marxists (GIM), the then German section of the Fourth International.
[src:andrea-fischer/andrea-fischer] From 1994 to 2002 she was a member of the German Bundestag.
[src:andrea-fischer/andrea-fischer] After the 1998 federal elections, she was appointed Federal Minister of Health on 27 October 1998, as a member of the federal government headed by Gerhard Schröder.
[src:andrea-fischer/andrea-fischer] She resigned from office on 9 January 2001 in the wake of the BSE crisis.
[src:andrea-fischer/andrea-fischer] Shortly afterwards, the resignation of the Federal Minister of Agriculture, Karl-Heinz Funke, was also announced.
[src:andrea-fischer/andrea-fischer] In the film *Schlachtfeld Politik – Die finstere Seite der Macht* (*Battlefield Politics – The dark side of power*) by Stephan Lamby, she describes that there was massive pressure from the party leadership.
[src:andrea-fischer/andrea-fischer] The film asks whether Andrea Fischer had to resign after *Joschka Fischer's wild years* (Der Spiegel edition 2/2001), not so much because of the BSE crisis as to relieve Joschka Fischer.
[src:andrea-fischer/andrea-fischer] Fischer was elected as the leading Alliance 90/The Greens candidate in the Berlin election on 18 September 2011, in the district assembly (*Bezirksverordnetenversammlung*) of Berlin's Mitte borough, where she was chair of the Alliance 90/The Greens parliamentary group until 30 October 2012.
[src:andrea-fischer/andrea-fischer] On 15 October 2012 Fischer was elected by the Regional Assembly to the office of Finance Director of the Hanover Region, which had been restructured by Regional President Hauke Jagau.
[src:andrea-fischer/andrea-fischer] It manages the areas of finance, facility management and hospitals.
[src:andrea-fischer/andrea-fischer] In April 2013 she took over as chairman of the supervisory board of the *Klinikum Region Hanover*.
[src:andrea-fischer/andrea-fischer] After her time as an active politician, Fischer became active as a freelance publicist and lobbyist in international health policy.
[src:andrea-fischer/andrea-fischer] From 2001 to 2009 she was patron of the *Federal Association of Experienced Psychiatrists* (*Bundesverband Psychiatrie-Erfahrener*).
[src:andrea-fischer/andrea-fischer] From 2004 to 2006 Fischer was a member of the management team of the consulting firm *Institut für Organisationskommunikation* (IFOK GmbH), where she was responsible for health and nutrition.
[src:andrea-fischer/andrea-fischer] Previously, she was head of the Center of Canadian Universities (CUC) in Berlin.
[src:andrea-fischer/andrea-fischer] Fischer is Vice Chairwoman of the Board of Trustees of the Institute of Man, Ethics and Science (*Institut Mensch, Ethik und Wissenschaft*).
[src:andrea-fischer/andrea-fischer] From 2006 to 2009 she worked at the PR agency Pleon in Munich, where she headed the medical-pharmaceutical area of healthcare.
[src:andrea-fischer/andrea-fischer] Since then she has been self-employed in this field.
[src:andrea-fischer/andrea-fischer] Since April 2006, Fischer has been co-editor of *GesundheitsNachrichten*, a specialist journal for the health industry.
[src:andrea-fischer/andrea-fischer] From October 2002 to the end of 2003, Andrea Fischer and BamS editor-in-chief Claus Strunz hosted the n-tv programme *Grüner Salon*.
[src:andrea-fischer/andrea-fischer] She appears regularly in broadcasts on Deutschlandradio Kultur, where she presents new publications of German-language crime literature.
[src:andrea-fischer/andrea-fischer] Fischer supported the Berlin Pro-Reli campaign, which failed in April 2009, as a testimonial.
[src:andrea-fischer/andrea-fischer] Since 2008 she has been the diocesan leader of the Malteser Hilfsdienst in Berlin.
[src:andrea-fischer/andrea-fischer] As a young woman, Fischer left the Catholic Church, into which she rejoined a good twenty years later.
